/|work=National Post|accessdate=March 9, 2011|date=September 22, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2011}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|LaHair Bryan|[[Bryan LaHair]]}}\n|{{sort|Iowa Cubs|[[Iowa Cubs]]}}||{{sort|Chicago Cubs|[[Chicago Cubs]]}}||[[First baseman]]||<ref>\n{{cite web|title=Cubs bring up PCL MVP LaHair|url=http://www.sacbee.com/2011/09/02/3880776/cubs-bring-up-pcl-mvp-lahair.html|work=The Sacramento Bee|accessdate=September 2, 2011|date=September 2, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2012}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|Eaton Adam|[[Adam Eaton (outfielder)|Adam Eaton]]}}\n|{{sort|Reno Aces|[[Reno Aces]]}}||{{sort|Arizona Diamondbacks|[[Arizona Diamondbacks]]}}||[[Outfielder]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120830&content_id=37602122&fext=.jsp&vkey=pr_milb|title=Eaton is PCL's Most Valuable Player|date=August 30, 2012|publisher=MILB.com|accessdate=August 1, 2013|location=Round Rock, Texas}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2013}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|Owings Chris|[[Chris Owings]]}}\n|{{sort|Reno Aces|[[Reno Aces]]}}||{{sort|Arizona Diamondbacks|[[Arizona Diamondbacks]]}}||[[Shortstop]]||<ref>[http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130829&content_id=58935682&vkey=pr_milb&fext=.jsp&sid=milb MiLB.com \u2013 Aces' Owings is 2013 PCL MVP]</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2014}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|Pederson Joc|[[Joc Pederson]]}}\n|{{sort|Albuquerque Isotopes|[[Albuquerque Isotopes]]}}||{{sort|Los Angeles Dodgers|[[Los Angeles Dodgers]]}}||[[Outfielder]]||<ref name=\"milb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140828&content_id=91909354&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_l112&sid=l112|title=PCL MVP goes to Isotopes' Pederson &#124; Pacific Coast League News|publisher=MILB.com|accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2015}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|Duffy Matt|[[Matt Duffy (baseball, born 1989)|Matt Duffy]]}}\n|{{sort|Fresno Grizzlies|[[Fresno Grizzlies]]}}||{{sort|Houston Astros|[[Houston Astros]]}}||[[Third baseman]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150903&content_id=147171062&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_l112&sid=l112|title=Duffy seizes Most Valuable Player Award|publisher=MILB.com|date=September 3, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2016}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sortname|Hunter|Renfroe}}\n|[[El Paso Chihuahuas]]||[[San Diego Padres]]||[[Outfielder]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160901&content_id=198980730&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_l112&sid=l112|title=Chihuahuas' Renfroe awarded Most Valuable Player|publisher=MILB.com|date=September 1, 2016|accessdate=September 1, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2017}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sortname|Christian|Walker|dab=baseball}}\n|[[Reno Aces]]||[[Arizona Diamondbacks]]||[[First baseman]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/pacific-coast/news/aces-walker-honored-as-pcls-most-valuable-player/c-251816392|title=Aces' Walker honored as PCL's Most Valuable Player|publisher=MILB.com|date=September 1, 2017|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2018}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sortname|Josh|Fuentes}}\n|[[Albuquerque Isotopes]]||[[Colorado Rockies]]||[[Third baseman]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/pacific-coast/news/albuquerques-fuentes-named-most-valuable-player/c-292731390|title=Albuquerque's Fuentes named Most Valuable Player|publisher=MILB.com|date=August 31, 2018|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{baseball year|2019}}\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sortname|Ty|France}}\n|[[El Paso Chihuahuas]]||[[San Diego Padres]]||[[Third baseman]]||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/pacific-coast/news/el-pasos-france-named-mvp/c-310426332|title=El Paso's France Named MVP|publisher=MILB.com|date=August 30, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[International League Most Valuable Player Award]]\n*[[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award]]\n*[[Baseball awards#U.S. minor leagues]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{PCL MVPs}}\n{{Pacific Coast League}}\n\n[[Category:Pacific Coast League MVP award winners| ]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1927]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Pacific Coast League<br>Most Valuable Player Award\n| current_awards = \n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| description    = Pacific Coast League's Regular Season MVP\n| presenter      = \n| host           = \n| location       = \n| country        = United States\n| reward         = [[Charlie Graham|Charles H. Graham]] Plaque<br>(formerly a cash reward)<ref name=metk />\n| year           = 1927\n| year2          = \n| holder         = [[Ty France]]\n| website        = \n}}\nThe '''Pacific Coast League Most Valuable Player Award''' ('''MVP''') is an annual award given to the best player in [[Minor League Baseball]]'s [[Pacific Coast League]] (PCL). [[Manager (baseball)|Managers]] from the 16 Pacific Coast League teams vote for the winner of the award, which is then combined with 16 votes from various [[general managers]], broadcasters, and media representatives around the league to determine a winner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arencibia wins PCL MVP award|url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100903&content_id=14234162&vkey=pr_l112&fext=.jsp&sid=l112|website=Pacific Coast League|publisher=Minor League Baseball|accessdate=March 11, 2011|date=June 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fernandez 2nd in PCL MVP Voting|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SLTB&p_theme=sltb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=100E914AF5FBAB5E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|url-access=subscription |accessdate=March 9, 2011|date=September 29, 2001}}</ref><ref name=greenmilb /> The award was formerly voted upon by writers from ''[[The Sporting News]]''.<ref name=\"jigger\">{{cite book|last=Medeiros|first=Paul J. Zingg, Mark D.|title=Runs, Hits, and an Era: The Pacific Coast League, 1903\u201358|year=1994|publisher=Published for the Oakland Museum by the University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|isbn=0-252-06402-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/runshitsanderapa00zing/page/89 89]|url=https://archive.org/details/runshitsanderapa00zing/page/89}}</ref><ref name=dom />\n\nIn 1927, [[Lefty O'Doul]] won the first Pacific Coast League MVP Award.<ref name=\"lefty\">{{cite web|last=McKenna|first=Brian|title=Lefty O'Doul|url=http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&pid=10559&bid=2674|work=Society for American Baseball Research|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=March 10, 2011}}</ref> No player was selected from 1928 to 1931. In 1932, the award returned, going to [[Jigger Statz]]. For six seasons in the 1970s (1973, 1975\u20131979) the award was suspended. In 1948, [[Charlie Graham]] donated a plaque, which was named in his honor, to be awarded annually to the league's MVP.<ref name=metk>{{cite web|title=Padres Still In Running|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fkwKAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4koDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6422,2192976&dq=metkovich+pacific+coast+league+most+valuable+player&hl=en|agency=Associated Press|work=Ellensburg Daily Record|accessdate=March 10, 2011|date=October 6, 1950}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=San Diego's Jack Graham Garners Loop Award|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/416872441.html?dids=416872441:416872441&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+21%2C+1948&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=San+Diego%27s+Jack+Graham+Garners+Loop+Award&pqatl=google|work=The Los Angeles Times|url-access=subscription |accessdate=March 10, 2011|date=September 21, 1948}}</ref>\n\n[[First basemen]], with 22 winners, have won the most among [[infielders]], followed by [[third basemen]] (8), [[second basemen]] (3), and [[shortstop]]s (3). Eight players who won the award were [[catcher]]s. Twenty-eight [[outfielder]]s have won the MVP Award, the most of any position. A total of 11&nbsp;pitchers have won the MVP Award, all of them being right-handed. The last pitcher to win was [[Steve Mintz]] in 1996. The Pacific Coast League now has a [[Pacific Coast League Pitcher of the Year Award|Pitcher of the Year Award]], which was established in 2001. [[Steve Bilko]] has the record for most MVP Award wins with three (1955\u20131957).<ref name=bilko /> [[Sandy Alomar, Jr.]], and [[Les Scarsella]] have both won the MVP Award twice. Scarsella first won the award in 1944 as a first baseman and then won his second in 1946 as an outfielder. Two PCL MVP Award winners, [[Joe DiMaggio]] and [[Tony P\u00e9rez]], have gone on to be inducted in the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]].<ref name=\"HOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/hof.shtml|title=Baseball Hall of Fame Inductees|website=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=December 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSeven players each from the [[Los Angeles Angels (PCL)|Los Angeles Angels]] and [[Las Vegas 51s|Las Vegas Stars/51s]] have been selected for the MVP Award, more than any other teams in the league, followed by the [[Albuquerque Dukes]] and [[San Diego Padres (PCL)|San Diego Padres]] (6); the [[Hollywood Stars]] (5); the [[Oakland Oaks (PCL)|Oakland Oaks]], [[Sacramento River Cats]], [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]], and [[Spokane Indians]] (4); the [[Calgary Cannons]], [[Reno Aces]], [[Seattle Rainiers]], and [[Tucson Sidewinders|Tucson Toros/Sidewinders]] (3); the [[Albuquerque Isotopes]], [[Edmonton Trappers]], [[El Paso Chihuahuas]], [[Fresno Grizzlies]], [[Iowa Cubs]], [[Oklahoma City Dodgers|Oklahoma City 89ers/Oklahoma RedHawks]], [[Phoenix Firebirds]], [[Sacramento Solons]], and [[Salt Lake City Bees]] (2); and the [[Eugene Emeralds]], [[Indianapolis Indians]], [[Omaha Royals]], [[Salt Lake Stingers]], [[Tacoma Rainiers|Tacoma Giants]], and [[Tulsa Oilers (baseball)|Tulsa Oilers]] (1).\n\nThirteen players from the [[Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn/Los Angeles Dodgers]] [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) organization have won the MVP Award, more than any other, followed by the [[Chicago Cubs]] organization (9); the [[San Diego Padres]] organization (6); the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], [[Houston Astros]], [[Oakland Athletics]], and [[San Francisco Giants]] organizations (4); the [[Chicago White Sox]], [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], [[Seattle Mariners]], and [[St. Louis Cardinals]] organizations (3); the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|Anaheim/California Angels]], [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Philadelphia Phillies]], [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], and [[Toronto Blue Jays]] organizations (2); and the [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Colorado Rockies]], [[Kansas City Royals]], and [[New York Yankees]] organizations (1). Thirteen MVP Award winners were not members of any MLB organization.\n\n==Key==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:85%\"\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Year'''\n|Links to an article about the corresponding year in baseball\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Position'''\n|Indicates the player's primary [[Baseball positions|position]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Small|(#)}}\n|Number of wins by players who won the award multiple times\n|}\n\n==Winners==\n[[File:Lefty-odoul.jpg|thumb|alt=Frank \"Lefty\" O'Doul in a New York Yankees uniform.|[[Lefty O'Doul]] won the first Pacific Coast League Most Valuable Player Award in 1927.<ref name=\"lefty\"/>]]\n[[File:DiMaggio cropped.jpg|thumb|alt=Joe DiMaggio at the 1937 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|[[Joe DiMaggio]], the 1935 winner, went on to win three [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|American League MVP Awards]] and was inducted in the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1955.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/dimagjo01.shtml|title=Joe DiMaggio Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=November 1, 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Steve Bilko.jpg|thumb|alt=A baseball card illustrating Steve Bilko in a St. Louis Cardinals uniform.|[[Steve Bilko]] won three consecutive PCL MVP Awards from 1955 to 1957.]]\n[[File:Tony Perez All Star Parade 2008.jpg|thumb|alt=Tony P\u00e9rez at the 2008 All-Star Game Red Carpet Parade|[[Tony P\u00e9rez]], the 1964 MVP, was inducted in the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 2000.<ref name=HOF/>]]\n[[File:Sandy Alomar, Jr. on June 29, 2012.jpg|thumb|alt=Sandy Alomar, Jr., wearing a gray baseball uniform with \"Cleveland\" across the chest|[[Sandy Alomar, Jr.]], who won back-to-back in 1988 and 1989, won the [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|American League Rookie of the Year Award]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/a/alomasa02.shtml|title=Sandy Alomar Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=November 1, 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Geovany Soto 2010.jpg|thumb|alt=Geovany Soto kneeling in a white baseball uniform with blue pinstripes and catcher's gear|[[Geovany Soto]] was the 2007 PCL MVP and the 2008 [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|National League Rookie of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/s/sotoge01.shtml|title=Geovany Soto Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=November 1, 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Christian Walker and Terrance Gore (34704604521) (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=Christian Walker making a play at first base|[[Christian Walker (baseball)|Christian Walker]] won the award in 2017.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Winner\n!scope=\"col\"|Team\n!scope=\"col\"|Or