{"title_page": "1997 New York Mets season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = New York Mets\n| season = 1997\n| misc = \n| logo = NewYorkMets.gif\n| current league = National League\n| y1 = 1962\n| division = [[National League East|Eastern Division]]\n| y2 = 1969\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Shea Stadium]]\n| y4 = 1964\n| city = New York\n| y5 = 1962\n| owners = [[Fred Wilpon]] and [[Nelson Doubleday, Jr.]]\n| general managers = [[Joe McIlvaine]], [[Steve Phillips]]\n| managers = [[Bobby Valentine]]\n| television = [[WWOR-TV]]/[[SportsChannel America|SportsChannel New York]]<br>([[Ralph Kiner]], [[Tim McCarver]], [[Fran Healy (baseball)|Fran Healy]], [[Howie Rose]], [[Gary Thorne]])\n| radio = [[WFAN]]<br>([[Bob Murphy (announcer)|Bob Murphy]], [[Gary Cohen]], [[Ed Coleman (radio personality)|Ed Coleman]])<br>[[WADO]] (spanish)<br>(Juan Alicea, [[Billy Berroa]]) \n}}\n\nThe '''[[New York Mets]]' 1997 season''' was the 36th regular season for the Mets. They went 88-74 and finished 3rd in the NL East. They were managed by [[Bobby Valentine]]. They played home games at [[Shea Stadium]].\n\n==Offseason==\n* November 25, 1996: [[Paul Byrd]] and a player to be named later were traded by the Mets to the [[Atlanta Braves]] for [[Greg McMichael]]. The Mets completed the deal by sending Andy Zwirchitz (minors) to the Braves on May 25, 1997.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/b/byrdpa01.shtml Paul Byrd page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* November 27, 1996: [[Rico Brogna]] was traded by the Mets to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for [[Ricardo Jordan]] and [[Toby Borland]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/b/brognri01.shtml Rico Brogna page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* December 20, 1996: [[Robert Person]] was traded by the Mets to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for [[John Olerud]] and cash.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/o/olerujo01.shtml John Olerud page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* March 22, 1997: [[H\u00e9ctor Ram\u00edrez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Ram\u00edrez]] was traded by the Mets to the [[Baltimore Orioles]] for [[Scott McClain]] and [[Manny Alexander]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcclasc01.shtml Scott McClain page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\nFor the first time since 1990 the Mets finished the regular season with a winning record. Their offensive output was led by their corner infielders, the 23-year old third baseman [[Edgardo Alfonzo]] and the two-time former world champion first baseman [[John Olerud]], the latter of whom was acquired in a trade with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]]. Alfonzo, in his first full season as a starter, led the team with a .315 average and 163 hits while Olerud notched a .294 average and drove in 102 runs to lead the Mets in that category. Catcher [[Todd Hundley]], a year removed from his record setting 1996 campaign, led the team in home runs with thirty and added 86 RBI, one of five Mets to record 70 or more (joining Alfonzo, Olerud, [[Bernard Gilkey]], and [[Butch Huskey]]).\n\nAfter a year out of baseball, [[Rick Reed (pitcher)|Rick Reed]] joined the Mets' starting rotation and led them with a 2.89 ERA. Bobby Jones led with fifteen wins, with Reed recording thirteen. [[John Franco]] saved 36 games, his most since 1988.\n\n===Jackie Robinson tribute===\nOn April 15 the Mets hosted ceremonies marking the 50th anniversary of [[Jackie Robinson]]'s first game with the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]] before their game against the Los Angeles Dodgers at [[Shea Stadium]].<ref name=Robinson>{{cite news|title=A Grand Tribute to Robinson and His Moment|date=April 16, 1997|first=Claire|last=Smith|newspaper=New York Times|page=A1}}</ref> The ceremony was attended by President [[Bill Clinton]] and commissioner [[Bud Selig]] announced that Robinson's jersey number, 42, would be retired permanently across baseball.<ref name=Robinson/> The Mets won the game 5-0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mets' Own Melting Pot Provides Victory Blend|date=April 16, 1997|first=Buster|last=Olney|newspaper=New York Times|page=B14|authorlink=Buster Olney}}</ref>\n\n===Subway Series===\n[[Interleague play]] was brought to MLB in 1997 and the Mets played [[New York Yankees]] in June as part of the first ever regular season games that counted in the standings between the two teams (they had previously an exhibition game until 1983 during the season). The series took place at [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]], and Mets won the first game by a score of 6-0.<ref>http://www.baseball-almanac.com/box-scores/boxscore.php?boxid=199706160NYA</ref>\n\n===Season standings===\n{{1997 NL East standings|highlight=New York Mets}}\n\n===Record vs. opponents===\n{{1997 NL Record vs. opponents|team=NYM}}\n\n===Notable transactions===\n* June 3, 1997: [[1997 Major League Baseball Draft]]\n**[[Garrett Atkins]] was drafted by the Mets in the 10th round, but did not sign.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/a/atkinga01.shtml Garrett Atkins page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n**[[Jeremy Guthrie]] was drafted by the Mets in the 15th round, but did not sign.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/g/guthrje01.shtml Jeremy Guthrie page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n* August 8, 1997: [[Lance Johnson]] and players to be named later were traded by the Mets to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for [[Brian McRae]], [[Mel Rojas]] and [[Turk Wendell]]. The Mets completed the deal by sending [[Mark Clark (baseball)|Mark Clark]] to the Cubs on August 11 and [[Manny Alexander]] to the Cubs on August 14.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcraebr01.shtml Brian McRae page at Baseball Reference]</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color: #003581; color: #f47937; text-align: center;\" | 1997 New York Mets \n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"background-color: #f47937; color: white; text-align: center;\" | '''Roster'''\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Pitchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|39|[[Juan Acevedo]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|46|[[Brian Bohanon]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|43|[[Toby Borland]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|54|[[Mark Clark (baseball)|Mark Clark]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|49|[[Joe Crawford (baseball)|Joe Crawford]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|31|[[John Franco]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|27|[[Pete Harnisch]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|44|[[Jason Isringhausen]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|28|[[Bobby Jones (right-handed pitcher)|Bobby Jones]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|48|[[Ricardo Jordan]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|18|[[Takashi Kashiwada]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|11|[[Cory Lidle]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|26|[[Barry Manuel]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Greg McMichael]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|38|[[Dave Mlicki]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|25|[[Yorkis P\u00e9rez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|35|[[Rick Reed (pitcher)|Rick Reed]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|40|[[Armando Reynoso]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|51|[[Mel Rojas]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|50|[[Ricky Trlicek]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|99|[[Turk Wendell]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" | \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Catchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|30|[[Alberto Castillo (catcher)|Alberto Castillo]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;9|[[Todd Hundley]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|43|[[Todd Pratt]]}}\n'''Infielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;6|[[Manny Alexander]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|13|[[Edgardo Alfonzo]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;8|[[Carlos Baerga]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|15|[[Matt Franco]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|12|[[Shawn Gilbert]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|19|[[Jason Hardtke]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|17|[[Luis L\u00f3pez (infielder)|Luis L\u00f3pez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[Kevin Morgan (baseball)|Kevin Morgan]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;5|[[John Olerud]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;0|[[Rey Ord\u00f3\u00f1ez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[Roberto Petagine]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" | \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Outfielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|29|[[Steve Bieser]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;3|[[Carl Everett]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Bernard Gilkey]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|42|[[Butch Huskey]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;1|[[Lance Johnson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|56|[[Brian McRae]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;6|[[Carlos Mendoza (baseball)|Carlos Mendoza]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|22|[[Alex Ochoa]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[Gary Thurman]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|33|[[Andy Tomberlin]]}}\n| width=\"25px\" | \n| va